                <alternative value="StatCrunch">
                    <title>StatCrunch Instructions</title>
                    <p> Here is how you conduct the z-test for the population proportion (p) in
                        StatCrunch.</p>
                    <p>There are two ways to perform the test, depending on whether you have
                        summarized values or the raw data.</p>
                    <p>If the data are summarized, as they are in our case (out of a random sample
                        of 316 airplanes, 40 were found to have contaminated water), then follow the
                        steps below.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose: Stat → Proportions → One Sample → with summary </li>

                        <li>Enter the number of successes and observations</li>
                        <li>Select Hypothesis Test for p</li>
                        <li>Enter a null value and choose the form of the alternative hypothesis
                            from the options not equal, less than, and greater than </li>
                        <li>Press Compute!</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>If you have raw data which consists of outcomes of individual trials, then
                        follow the steps below. </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose: Stat → Proportions → One Sample → with data </li>
                        <li>Values in: select column with sample data</li>
                        <li>Success: specify the value that denotes success.</li>
                        <li>Perform: select Hypothesis Test for p </li>
                        <li>Enter a null value and choose the form of the alternative hypothesis
                            from the options not equal, less than, and greater than</li>
                        <li>Choose from the options of not equal, less than and greater than for the
                            alternative hypothesis. </li>
                        <li>Press Compute! </li>
                    </ul>
                </alternative>

                <alternative value="minitab">
                    <title>Minitab Instructions</title>
                    <p>Here is how you conduct the z-test for the population proportion (p) in
                        Minitab:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Choose: Stat → Basic Statistics → 1 Proportion</li>
                        <li>Enter the data. There are two ways to perform the test, depending on
                            whether you have the raw data, or summarized values: <ul>
                                <li>If you have the raw data in a Minitab worksheet, choose the
                                    "Samples in columns" option, and enter the column containing the
                                    data.</li>
                                <li>If the data are summarized, as they are in our case (out of a
                                    random sample of 316 airplanes, 40 were found to have
                                    contaminated water), enter the sample size, and how many of the
                                    subjects have the characteristic of interest.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li>Click on "Options" <ul>
                                <li>Next to "Test proportion," enter the null value, <m:math
                                        overflow="scroll">
                                        <m:mrow>
                                            <m:msub>
                                                <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                            </m:msub>
                                        </m:mrow>
                                    </m:math>. </li>
                                <li>Choose the relevant alternative.</li>
                                <li>Check "Use this....normal distribution."</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li>Click "OK" twice.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><em>Comment:</em> As we mentioned above, if the raw data are given we can
                        (instead of giving the summarized values) tell Minitab what column the raw
                        data are in. Click <link href="../../../webcontent/minitab/water-raw.mtw"
                            >here</link> to open Minitab with the raw data of this study, and verify
                        that when you run the test, you get the same output. </p>
                </alternative>
                <alternative value="excel">
                    <title>Excel 2013 and 2016 Instructions</title>
                    <p>To conduct the z-test for the population proportion (p) in Excel, we first
                        need to calculate <m:math display="inline">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>, and to do this, we remember that <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mn>X</m:mn>
                                    <m:mn>n</m:mn>
                                </m:mfrac>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>. Now we can calculate the test statistic using <m:math
                            display="inline">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mrow>
                                        <m:mover>
                                            <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                            <m:mo stretchy="true">ˆ</m:mo>
                                        </m:mover>
                                        <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                        <m:msub>
                                            <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                        </m:msub>
                                    </m:mrow>
                                    <m:msqrt>
                                        <m:mfrac>
                                            <m:mrow>
                                                <m:msub>
                                                  <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                                  <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                                </m:msub>
                                                <m:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                                  <m:mrow>
                                                  <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                                                  <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                                  <m:msub>
                                                  <m:mi>p</m:mi>
                                                  <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                                  </m:msub>
                                                  </m:mrow>
                                                </m:mfenced>
                                            </m:mrow>
                                            <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                        </m:mfrac>
                                    </m:msqrt>
                                </m:mfrac>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>. </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Once we have calculated our test statistic (z), we find the probability
                            that p is less than or equal to the test statistic (z) using the Excel
                            formula <code style="inline">=NORM.S.DIST(z, cumulative)</code> Remember
                            to put TRUE for cumulative when using this function.</li>
                        <li>Since our alternative hypothesis is that p is <code style="inline"
                                >greater than</code> z, we then find the p-value that we want by
                            subtracting the value we just calculated from 1.</li>
                    </ul>
                </alternative>
